        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Which now connects up for me with "
              },
              {
                "type": "link",
                "url": "https://futureofcoding.org/episodes/061",
                "text": "the podcast episode on Programming as Theory-building"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ": a lot of \"understanding\" a program comes from figuring out which inputs to pass to it. And I don't mean just some static list of inputs captured in a unit test. You learn the broad categories of phenomena you can expect from a domain, akin to "
              },
              {
                "type": "link",
                "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-body_problem",
                "text": "the kinds of orbits people have discovered so far for the 3-body problem"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ". I've learned knacks like this from working with others in the past.\n\n(Apologies if all this seems too much of a tangent to the original thread. I can start a fresh one if so.)"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
